    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-04T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-04T10:00:00-05:00" n="627"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d627">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1850</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-04T16:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 4, 1915, 4 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.20 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2369. Department’s 1770. Asked <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName>
                    for report <hi rend="italic">Nebraskan.</hi> Says he knows of none, but will ask
                    Marine Department. In conversation I gathered there is little chance of Germany
                    giving up torpedoing without notice unless England will allow entrance copper,
                    cotton, rubber, and raw material not directly used for munitions of war.
                    Prospect our breaking diplomatic relations foreshadowed in papers here does not
                    worry German Government in the least. They do not believe we will declare war.
                    He said he labored under great <pb facs="0691" n="433" xml:id="pg_433"/>
                    disadvantage in not being able to get Washington sentiment from <persName
                        corresp="#p_BJHACV1">Von Bernstorff</persName>. There is a remote chance of
                    Germany arranging not to torpedo enemy ships carrying American passengers if
                    such ships are certified by American authorities or consuls as not having
                    munitions on board or cannon or arms and such ships must not ram submarine
                    boats. Arrangements might be made for limited number of such ships with special
                    flags.</p>
                <p>Germany probably putting ten new submarine boats a month in water. Cannot see why
                    raw material proposal not accepted, it will benefit us. Germany has plenty of
                    food and raw material for war purposes. Needs raw material for industry.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
